# 🚀 🧠 Complete Workflow for Your First Django App

## 🔹 1. Development Phase (Local / EC2)

You already did this 👇

```text
Create Django project → Test locally → Run server
```

Commands:

```bash
django-admin startproject myproject
cd myproject
python manage.py runserver
```

---

## 🔹 2. Add Requirements (Dependency management)

Create:

```bash
vim requirements.txt
```

Add:

```text
Django==4.2.11
gunicorn
```

👉 This makes your app reproducible

---

## 🔹 3. Dockerize the App

You already did this too 👇

### Dockerfile

```dockerfile
FROM python:3.9-slim

WORKDIR /app

COPY . .

RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

EXPOSE 8000

CMD ["python", "manage.py", "runserver", "0.0.0.0:8000"]
```

---

## 🔹 4. Build & Run Container

```bash
docker build -t django-app .
docker run -it -p 8000:8000 django-app
```

---

## 🔹 5. Fix Production Basics

### ✅ settings.py

```python
ALLOWED_HOSTS = ["*"]
```

---

## 🔹 6. Push Image to Docker Hub

```bash
docker tag django-app yourusername/django-app
docker push yourusername/django-app
```

---

## 🔹 7. Pull & Run on Another Server

```bash
docker pull yourusername/django-app
docker run -d -p 8000:8000 yourusername/django-app
```

---

# 🔥 Now the REAL DevOps workflow begins

---

## 🔹 8. Replace runserver with Gunicorn (Production)

Update Dockerfile:

```dockerfile
CMD ["gunicorn", "--bind", "0.0.0.0:8000", "myproject.wsgi:application"]
```

---

## 🔹 9. Add Nginx (Reverse Proxy)

Real architecture:

```text
User → Nginx → Gunicorn → Django
```

Why:

* better performance
* security
* static file handling

---

## 🔹 10. Use Docker Compose (Multi-container)

Example:

```text
Django + PostgreSQL + Redis + Nginx
```

---

## 🔹 11. CI/CD Pipeline (Automation)

Flow:

```text
GitHub → Jenkins/GitHub Actions → Build → Push → Deploy
```

---

## 🔹 12. Deploy to Cloud (AWS)

Options:

* EC2 (you are here now ✅)
* ECS / EKS (next level)

---

